</P>
<P>
WRONG BOLTS CITED IN AIR MISHAP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LONDON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The use of improper bolts probably caused a cockpit windshield to blow out of a 
British Airways plane at 23,000 feet during the weekend, almost sucking the 
pilot out of the aircraft, officials said today. 
</P>
<P>
"Investigators have determined that of the 90 bolts used to retain the 
windscreen, 84 were of an incorrect size for the captive nuts into which they 
were installed," a Civil Aviation Authority official said. 
</P>
<P>
"This explains the windscreen's blowing out when exposed to the cabin pressure 
during the climb." 
</P>
<P>
Officials reported the incorrect bolts were 1.5 inches in diameter, 1/32 of an 
inch smaller than they should have been. 
</P>
<P>
British Airways said it has suspended the engineer responsible for fitting the 
bolts, pending completion of the inquiry by government investigators. 
</P>
</TEXT>
