</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIZ SMITH: CAN ALL THE NEGATIVE PUBLICITY TRIP UP TRUMP? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LIZ SMITH 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"TRUMP IS the victim of his own peculiar naivete about the way life works. 
Couldn't he see what all of his shameless self-promotion was setting him up 
for? Schadenfreude -- a German word for glee over the misfortune of others -- 
is actually as American as casino gambling," writes Jonathan Alter in the 
current Newsweek. 
</P>
<P>
These thoughts come under Alter's heading "The Fame Game: Why Everyone's 
Gloating," in the magazine's cover story, "Trump: The Fall." 
</P>
<P>
IT IS in this issue that Donald Trump is quoted, saying: "Negative publicity 
has no effect in my life." 
</P>
<P>
If this is true, then Donald is in a class by himself. Negative publicity 
almost always takes its toll, however, in psychic distress if nowhere else. But 
then, matters tend to settle, so that the public makes final perceptions and 
summings-up of high profile people that usually are pretty much correct. 
</P>
<P>
The function of the press, with all its hits and errors, is to add to this 
ability of people in general to draw fairly accurate conclusions. And, as 
Americans are more prone to be fair than to be unfair, somehow most stories 
work out on the fair side. 
</P>
<P>
I SUPPOSE the press can't be blamed too much for falling for that elaborate and 
absurd hoax about Elizabeth Taylor's 23-year-old "new love." But anybody who 
has ever dealt with Taylor's formidable press rep, Chen Sam, immediately 
recognized this story as a fake. Never in a million years would Chen (or anyone 
working for her) dare to talk of Elizabeth's "depression" or of her intimate 
affairs. They particularly wouldn't make those National Enquirer-type quotes. 
</P>
<P>
In fact, bamboo shoots under the fingernails couldn't make Chen Sam, a woman 
with a rather blind-sided view of what constitutes her job, even tell you what 
color dress Elizabeth Taylor is wearing! 
</P>
<P>
KANIN GAININ' on marryin' Marian! Garson Kanin, the famous 
screenwriter-playwright-director par excellence, was wed for many happy years 
to the late actress Ruth Gordon. 
</P>
<P>
Since Ruth's death several years ago, Kanin has been keeping company with 
Broadway's most enduring actress, Marian Seldes. (She has appeared in two of 
the Great White Way's longest-running hits, "Equus" and "Deathtrap," and is 
currently in Chester, Conn., with the out-of-town "Annie II.") 
</P>
<P>
Now Kanin and Seldes plan to tie the knot on June 19 in New York City. It 
couldn't happen to a nicer couple. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Donald Trump 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA061390-0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 233203 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
June 13, 1990, Wednesday, P.M. Final 
</P>
